There are three words which occur in different documenta which seem to require some explanation·- Skonsessore on page 873 Lovecmfiy on page 1793 and Utviethis on page 264. Skomerfare occurs in Gower's Confessio Amantis, and in Halliwell’s Dictionary is de- scribed as meaning piracy. The derivation is given as from escnmerie, which certainly means piracy. This explanation is not altogether satisfactory, for Skomerfare is evidently a eompound word, and cannot be derived from escnmerie alone. In the Dover Chamberlains’ Accounts the tolls levied on various imports are invariable called “fare‚'' r.g., “Hokfare‚” ‘⁶ Herringfare‚” “Sprot- fare,” etc, and Slromerfare must accordingly be a toll levied on “Skomer.’' The word occurs occasionally in the accounts, and it will not be out of place to quote one or two instanccs of its use.

Es solut’ Iohanni Hannon pro qunsfcrre -— (Add. Mss, B.M., 29615, sol. 55).

Et in litteris desirendis pro nominibus de Mergatr . . . querendis pro vosagium de Skomersarr ad diversas vices- iiis. iid. (ib. sol. aab).

If we derive the word from escnmerie it would mean either the toll levied on all booty captured and landed out of pirate vessels, or, what is more probable, the proportion of profit which each masiner obtained as his share of the plunder. l am inclined to think the latter is the right local interpretation of the word, for the Warden, as the Admiral of the Cinque Porta, always claimed at least a share in the goods of pirates.
